section.t:
Shortest Path Bridging (SPB) [SPB] and TRILL [TRILL] are two different methods of IS-IS based overlay that operates over L2 Ethernets. They all use the MAC in MAC encapsulation and have the same default MAC address learning method: Using IS-IS extension for outer MAC address distribution over the SPB area or TRILL campus network;
Using ARP or data plane snooping for inner MAC address learning of locally attached hosts.
In addition, the TRILL maybe use [draft-ietf-trill-directory-framework] distributes the inner MAC address between all the RBriges

The ARMD WG examined data center scaling issues with a focus on address resolution and developed a problem statement document [RFC6820]. In this document, the scaling issues of MAC address learning related to the overlay-based approach are listed as followed: ARP processing on Routers: This issue mainly concerns about the significant amount of ARP traffic or BUM packets traffic in large L2 broadcast domains and its impact to the routers. Finally, some optimized method are proposed;
IPv6 Neighbor Discovery has the similar issue as ARP processing on router;
MAC Address Table Size Limitations at Switches: This issue mainly concerns on the MAC Address Table Size Limitations when the VM number is very large in the Virtualized data center environment.

VPLS is an L2 VPN technology. VPLS uses the ARP and data plane learning for L2 tenant system information discovery, and not advertised and distributed via a BGP/LDP control plane. The analysis of this method is as followed: Pros: Reducing complexity and work burden of the control plane by decreasing the control packets;
MAC address learning based on active flows can save the space of MAC mapping table. Cons: PE will learn all active MACs over the associated PW by BUM flooding of data plane. But, some active MACs is not destined to the PE;
Unlike the active MAC withdraw mechanism in control plane, PE cannot flush MAC address real-time in data plane, when host MACs behind the PE are changed.
